1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
This lesson is all about image optimization.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:09,000
But you might be asking what is image optimization all about?

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Image optimization maintains the balance of image quality while reducing file size.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:24,000
It is the process of delivering high-quality images in the ideal format, size and resolution to increase user engagement.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:32,000
It also involves accurately labeling images so search engines can read them and understand page content.

6
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Before moving forward, let's briefly talk about the advantages of image optimization.

7
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Image optimization will help you improve page loading speed, the user experience, SEO and it doesn't require any development skills.

8
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Image optimization clearly has a domino effect.

9
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:58,000
If your images load quickly, it will increase user engagement and then lead to improved search engine rankings.

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:01,000
So how do we optimize images?

11
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Firstly, we need to change the file name of an image before uploading and then add alternative text.

12
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Secondly, make sure you choose the correct image type.

13
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:18,000
And then we can also scale or crop an image and lastly compress the image file.

14
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:23,000
So make sure you change the file name of an image before uploading it to your media library.

15
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
And remember to add the alt text.

16
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:34,000
When you add an image to your media library, you can open it up and top-right it says Alternative text.

17
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:43,000
The alt tag is simply a brief text description of an image, but it explains the content of images to website users when a graphic can't be loaded.

18
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:52,000
It also allows search engines to better crawl and rank your website and it also helps visually impaired users to understand the content of a page.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:56,000
It is also important to note image SEO starts with the file name.

20
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
You want a search engine to know what the image is without even looking at it.

21
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:02,000
So use a focused key phrase.

22
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
WordPress lets you upload images in several formats.

23
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Most commonly, images are saved as JPEG, PNG, WebP or AVIF.

24
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
JPEG is typically used for photographs and images of people and objects.

25
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:27,000
PNG is suitable for graphics, illustrations and images with transparency, while WebP and AVIF are excellent choices for optimizing website performance,

26
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:34,000
especially for non-vectorized assets like photos and animations due to their superior compression capabilities.

27
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:41,000
I would also recommend avoiding GIFs as they present accessibility challenges.

28
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Lastly, we are going to look at three methods to optimize images.

29
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:54,000
Firstly, you can use a WordPress plugin or you may decide to use a web-based tool or an image editor.

30
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Let's start with plugins.

31
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:10,000
To add a plugin, let's make our way to Plugins, click on Add New and then type "Image optimization" in the search block.

32
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
Now you will notice there are many different plugins to choose from.

33
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:23,000
Some plugins worth exploring are Modern Image Formats, Image Optimization by Optimal, Smush or Imagify.

34
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:29,000
Please note, depending on the plugin, some features might only be supported by the Pro version.

35
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:35,000
For new image uploads on your site, you might want to consider using modern image formats.

36
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:39,000
This plugin has been created and is managed by the WordPress performance team.

37
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:46,000
And basically converts images to more modern formats such as WebP or AVIF during upload.

38
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:52,000
In this example, I am going to install and activate the EWWW Image Optimizer plugin.

39
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:59,000
Once activated, we can go to Settings and we will see an option that says "Optimize Local Images".

40
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:05,000
And if you scroll down, you will see more options that come with the premium package.

41
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:18,000
But if we make our way to media, we can click on Bulk Optimize and then scan for unoptimized images.

42
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:27,000
And there we can see we have 184 images to optimize and there are some more options on the right.

43
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:35,000
Next, let's explore some web based tools where you can optimize the image before uploading it to your WordPress site.

44
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Some options worth considering are tinypng.com, tinyimg.com, kraken.io and squoosh.app.

45
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Let's see how Squoosh works.

46
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:55,000
It's open source and supports all image formats.

47
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Once you add an image from your computer, you can edit or compress it.

48
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Firstly, I will click on Resize and then change the height of the image and you will notice the width automatically updates.

49
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:15,000
Next, I will go to Compress and save the image as a WebP file.

50
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:22,000
And bottom right, we can see that this file size has been reduced by 97%.

51
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Finally, you also have the option to use image editors such as Pixlr, Photopia, Gimp or Canva.

52
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:35,000
You might be asking what is an optimal size for use in WordPress?

53
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
Well, it depends on how you will use that image.

54
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:43,000
1200 by 628 pixels is a good size for header images.

55
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:53,000
For other images, an optimal size is at least 640 by 480 and up to around 1024 by 768 pixels.

56
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:58,000
I trust this information has been helpful and that you will find the right method that works for you.

